      <h1 class="font-heading text-4xl md:text-5xl tracking-wide text-primary mb-6">8 Signs You Need a New Roof in South Florida</h1>
      <p class="text-gray-400 text-sm mb-8">Updated January 2025 &middot; 5 min read</p>

      <div class="prose prose-gray max-w-none text-gray-600 leading-relaxed space-y-6">
        <p>Your roof is your home's first line of defense against South Florida's intense sun, heavy rain, and hurricane-season storms. But how do you know when repairs are no longer enough and it is time for a full replacement? Here are eight warning signs every Fort Lauderdale homeowner should watch for.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">1. Your Roof Is Over 20 Years Old</h2>
        <p>Most asphalt shingle roofs last 15 to 25 years in Florida's demanding climate. If your <a href="/service/residential-roofing" class="text-accent hover:underline">residential roof</a> is approaching or past the 20-year mark, it is time to start planning for a replacement, even if it looks okay from the ground. The underlying materials may be deteriorating beneath the surface.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">2. Missing, Cracked, or Curling Shingles</h2>
        <p>Shingles that are cracked, curled at the edges, or missing entirely indicate that your roof is failing. Damaged shingles expose the underlayment to water and UV damage, accelerating deterioration. A few damaged shingles can be repaired, but widespread damage typically warrants a full replacement.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">3. Water Stains on Ceilings or Walls</h2>
        <p>Brown or yellowish stains on your interior ceilings or walls are a clear sign of a roof leak. While some leaks can be patched, recurring water intrusion often means the roofing membrane has failed. Ignoring leaks can lead to mold growth, structural damage, and much higher repair costs down the road.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">4. Sagging Roof Deck</h2>
        <p>A visibly sagging roofline is a serious structural concern that demands immediate attention. Sagging usually indicates water damage to the roof decking or weakened structural supports. This issue requires professional evaluation and almost always means a full roof replacement is necessary.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">5. Granules in Your Gutters</h2>
        <p>If you notice excessive granules accumulating in your gutters or at the base of your downspouts, your shingles are losing their protective coating. Granule loss exposes the asphalt to UV rays, causing rapid deterioration. Some granule loss is normal on new roofs, but heavy shedding on older roofs is a replacement indicator.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">6. Rising Energy Bills</h2>
        <p>A failing roof allows hot air to penetrate your attic, making your air conditioning system work harder. If your energy bills have been increasing without a clear explanation, poor roof insulation or ventilation could be the cause. A new roof with modern materials like <a href="/service/metal-roofing" class="text-accent hover:underline">metal roofing</a> or reflective <a href="/service/roof-coatings" class="text-accent hover:underline">roof coatings</a> can significantly reduce cooling costs.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">7. Storm Damage</h2>
        <p>South Florida's hurricane season puts immense stress on roofs. Even if your roof survived a storm without visible damage, high winds and flying debris can compromise its integrity. After any major storm, schedule a professional inspection. <a href="/service/roof-maintenance" class="text-accent hover:underline">Regular roof maintenance</a> and post-storm inspections help catch hidden damage before it becomes a bigger problem.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">8. Daylight Through Roof Boards</h2>
        <p>If you can see daylight coming through the boards in your attic, your roof has gaps that allow water and pests to enter. This is an urgent sign that your roof needs immediate replacement. Even small gaps will worsen quickly in Florida's heavy rainstorms.</p>

        <h2 class="font-heading text-2xl tracking-wide text-primary mt-8 mb-4">What to Do Next</h2>
